04966nam a22007575i 9780801469824DE-B159720210830012106.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210830t20132013nyu    fo  d z      eng d  a(OCoLC)979630676  a97808014698247 a10.7591/97808014698242doi  a(DE-B1597)478585  a(OCoLC)862076564  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  anyucUS-NY 4aRA975.5.H6bZ83 2016 7aMED0430002bisacsh04a362.1106842231 aZuberi, Dan, eauthor.4aut4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/aut10aCleaning Up :bHow Hospital Outsourcing Is Hurting Workers and Endangering Patients /cDan Zuberi. 1aIthaca, NY : bCornell University Press, c[2013] 4c©2013  a1 online resource (200 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aThe Culture and Politics of Health Care Work00tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tAcknowledgments -- t1. “Stuff Gets Missed”: An Introduction to a Growing Health Care Crisis -- t2. Germs, Blood, and Cost-Cutting: The Daily Struggle to Keep Hospitals Clean -- t3. Compromising Cleanliness: How Outsourcing Keeps Hospital Workers from Doing Their Jobs -- t4. Untrained Workers, Unfit Managers -- t5. Breaking Up the Team -- t6. Down and Out in Vancouver: Struggling, Stressed, and Exhausted Hospital Support Workers -- t7. Cleaning Up -- tNotes -- tReferences -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aTo cut costs and maximize profits, hospitals in the United States and many other countries are outsourcing such tasks as cleaning and food preparation to private contractors. In Cleaning Up, the first book to examine this transformation in the healthcare industry, Dan Zuberi looks at the consequences of outsourcing from two perspectives: its impact on patient safety and its role in increasing socioeconomic inequality. Drawing on years of field research in Vancouver, Canada as well as data from hospitals in the U.S. and Europe, he argues that outsourcing has been disastrous for the cleanliness of hospitals—leading to an increased risk of hospital-acquired infections, a leading cause of severe illness and death—as well as for the effective delivery of other hospital services and the workers themselves.Zuberi's interviews with the low-wage workers who keep hospitals running uncover claims of exposure to near-constant risk of injury and illness. Many report serious concerns about the quality of the work due to understaffing, high turnover, poor training and experience, inadequate cleaning supplies, and on-the-job injuries. Zuberi also presents policy recommendations for improving patient safety by reducing the risk of hospital-acquired infection and ameliorating the work conditions and quality of life of hospital support workers. He makes the case that hospital outsourcing exemplifies the trend towards "low-road" service-sector jobs that threatens to undermine society's social health, as well as the physical health and well-being of patients in health care settings globally.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aHospital carexContracting outzBritish ColumbiazVancouver. 0aHospital carezBritish ColumbiazVancouverxSafety measures. 0aHospital housekeepingzBritish ColumbiazVancouver. 0aHospitalszBritish ColumbiazVancouverxEmployees. 0aNosocomial infectionszBritish ColumbiazVancouver. 4aConsumer Health & Fitness. 4aLabor History. 4aSociology & Social Science. 7aMEDICAL / Hospital Administration & Care.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013z978311053615740uhttps://doi.org/10.7591/978080146982440uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780801469824423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780801469824.jpg  a978-3-11-053615-7  Cornell University Press Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013 